# KijaniKiosk Access Model

## Purpose

The KijaniKiosk access model is designed around the principle of least privilege. Each service receives only the permissions required to perform its operational responsibilities.

## Users

### kk-api

Role:
Application API service.

Responsibilities:
- Reads application configuration.
- Writes application logs.
- Serves API requests.

Restrictions:
- No interactive login.
- Limited filesystem access.

### kk-payments

Role:
Payments processing service.

Responsibilities:
- Reads payments configuration.
- Processes payment transactions.
- Writes operational logs.

Restrictions:
- No interactive login.
- Isolated execution environment.

### kk-logs

Role:
Monitoring and logging service.

Responsibilities:
- Reads shared log files.
- Generates monitoring information.
- Maintains health reports.

Restrictions:
- No interactive login.
- Read-only access where possible.

## Group Structure

Group:
kijanikiosk

Purpose:
Provides controlled shared access between services.

## Directory Access Model

| Directory | Owner | Group | Purpose |
|------------|---------|---------|---------|
| Shared logs | Root | kijanikiosk | Shared application logs |
| Configuration | Root | kijanikiosk | Environment configuration |
| Health | kk-logs | kijanikiosk | Monitoring outputs |

## ACL Strategy

ACLs are used to allow:
- kk-api access to shared logs.
- kk-payments access to shared logs.
- Future log files to inherit permissions automatically.

## Logrotate Interaction

Default ACLs ensure newly created log files inherit the required access model after rotation.

This prevents service failures caused by permission changes after log maintenance operations.

## Health Directory Addition

A dedicated health directory was introduced to support monitoring outputs.

Ownership was assigned to the monitoring service to ensure:
- Health reports can be generated.
- Monitoring tools can access status information.
- Administrative intervention is not required.
